1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:07,140
[SPEAKER_07]: And after drawing lots, it was determined that Prime Minister Rishi Sunak, apparently the underdog, will be first to face a grilling in a very warm studio.

2
00:00:07,540 --> 00:00:08,481
[SPEAKER_07]: Minister, welcome.

3
00:00:09,122 --> 00:00:09,803
[SPEAKER_07]: Prime Minister, even.

4
00:00:09,963 --> 00:00:11,545
[SPEAKER_07]: Welcome back to Never Mind The Ballots.

5
00:00:11,565 --> 00:00:12,566
[SPEAKER_07]: Eric, thanks for having me back.

6
00:00:12,586 --> 00:00:13,027
[SPEAKER_07]: Good to be here.

7
00:00:13,427 --> 00:00:22,218
[SPEAKER_07]: When you resigned from Boris Johnson's government, your resignation letter said that the public rightly expects the government to be conducted properly, competently and seriously.

8
00:00:22,838 --> 00:00:25,802
[SPEAKER_07]: How do you feel you've upheld that as Prime Minister?

9
00:00:26,120 --> 00:00:28,844
[SPEAKER_06]: I've been Prime Minister for 18 months, give or take.

10
00:00:28,864 --> 00:00:33,811
[SPEAKER_06]: When I first came in, the priority I had was to make sure that we could restore economic stability.

11
00:00:34,232 --> 00:00:36,715
[SPEAKER_06]: And that was the challenge that everyone was facing with the cost of living.

12
00:00:37,076 --> 00:00:38,798
[SPEAKER_06]: And I said, look, this is what I'm about.

13
00:00:38,838 --> 00:00:40,321
[SPEAKER_06]: Those are the things I want to focus on.

14
00:00:40,441 --> 00:00:41,342
[SPEAKER_06]: You can judge me.

15
00:00:41,723 --> 00:00:44,747
[SPEAKER_06]: I want to be very clear and transparent about what I'm wanting to do for you.

16
00:00:44,787 --> 00:00:46,970
[SPEAKER_06]: And so the first of those was to bring down inflation.

17
00:00:47,010 --> 00:00:48,212
[SPEAKER_06]: And I'm pleased that

18
00:00:48,192 --> 00:00:52,018
[SPEAKER_06]: We've just got the news recently that inflation is back to normal, and that is a sign of progress.

19
00:00:52,218 --> 00:00:59,870
[SPEAKER_06]: I know people are only just starting to feel the benefits of that, but it shows that we're on the right track, and that's why we're able to start cutting people's taxes, and that's why I want to go further.

20
00:00:59,890 --> 00:01:01,673
[SPEAKER_07]: I want to pick up on one of those words, which is proper.

21
00:01:01,833 --> 00:01:02,154
[SPEAKER_07]: Properly.

22
00:01:02,374 --> 00:01:03,235
[SPEAKER_07]: Running the country properly.

23
00:01:03,255 --> 00:01:11,568
[SPEAKER_07]: Your closest aide, your bodyguard, your campaign manager and your head of data are all being investigated for what is essentially insider trading.

24
00:01:11,769 --> 00:01:12,630
[SPEAKER_06]: Is that proper?

25
00:01:13,150 --> 00:01:14,713
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, I was incredibly angry.

26
00:01:15,355 --> 00:01:21,568
[SPEAKER_06]: Incredibly angry when I learnt about the allegations, as everybody would be when they would hear about something like that.

27
00:01:21,869 --> 00:01:23,432
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, just to... Why haven't you suspended them?

28
00:01:23,452 --> 00:01:28,543
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, just to explain, so the Gambling Commission who are investigating these, as well as the police, obviously are independent.

29
00:01:28,523 --> 00:01:29,745
[SPEAKER_06]: of me, of government.

30
00:01:30,105 --> 00:01:32,669
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't have access to the details of their investigation.

31
00:01:32,729 --> 00:01:33,990
[SPEAKER_06]: They don't report to me.

32
00:01:34,411 --> 00:01:46,367
[SPEAKER_06]: But what I can tell you is, in parallel, we have been conducting internal inquiries of our own into the situation and won't hesitate to act when information or findings come to light.

33
00:01:46,387 --> 00:01:47,548
[SPEAKER_07]: Surely that can't take too long.

34
00:01:47,589 --> 00:01:50,953
[SPEAKER_07]: You just ask everyone in the room if they put a bet on when they found out about the election.

35
00:01:50,993 --> 00:01:51,694
[SPEAKER_07]: You were there.

36
00:01:51,734 --> 00:01:53,957
[SPEAKER_07]: You must have known who you told, right?

37
00:01:54,173 --> 00:01:56,835
[SPEAKER_06]: Harry, these are really serious matters.

38
00:01:57,436 --> 00:01:58,357
[SPEAKER_06]: You promised... And they're subject...

39
00:01:58,377 --> 00:01:59,178
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm just...

40
00:01:59,218 --> 00:02:00,118
[SPEAKER_06]: They're really serious.

41
00:02:00,178 --> 00:02:04,963
[SPEAKER_06]: They're subject to multiple independent investigations, including a police criminal investigation.

42
00:02:05,003 --> 00:02:12,570
[SPEAKER_06]: It's right that nothing that I do or anyone does compromises the integrity of those investigations, and you understand that.

43
00:02:12,590 --> 00:02:21,217
[SPEAKER_06]: But I want to reassure people, we are in parallel and have been conducting internal inquiries and won't hesitate to act if findings or information comes to light.

44
00:02:21,237 --> 00:02:24,180
[SPEAKER_06]: And I've been crystal clear, if anyone has broken the rules,

45
00:02:24,160 --> 00:02:28,708
[SPEAKER_06]: then they should face not just the full consequences of the law, but they will be booted out of the Conservative Party.

46
00:02:28,728 --> 00:02:33,517
[SPEAKER_07]: What does it say about your leadership, though, that people so close to you felt that that wasn't a problem?

47
00:02:33,537 --> 00:02:40,970
[SPEAKER_07]: You promised integrity, professionalism and accountability when you were the new broom to come in and fix the Tory woes when you took after Boris Johnson and Liz Truss.

48
00:02:41,771 --> 00:02:43,755
[SPEAKER_07]: How does this stack up with integrity?

49
00:02:44,022 --> 00:02:46,087
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, Harry, we're doing exactly... You talked to...

50
00:02:46,147 --> 00:02:46,909
[SPEAKER_07]: They felt...

51
00:02:46,969 --> 00:02:52,843
[SPEAKER_07]: They felt able to go down the bookies as soon as you let them know that there was an election coming.

52
00:02:52,924 --> 00:02:53,846
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, who are you employing?

53
00:02:54,066 --> 00:02:55,630
[SPEAKER_06]: Harry, you should just be careful.

54
00:02:55,670 --> 00:02:58,437
[SPEAKER_06]: There are independent inquiries ongoing.

55
00:02:59,193 --> 00:03:00,254
[SPEAKER_06]: Those haven't concluded.

56
00:03:00,294 --> 00:03:03,117
[SPEAKER_06]: They're being done by very serious bodies.

57
00:03:04,018 --> 00:03:07,602
[SPEAKER_06]: The Gambling Commission and the police.

58
00:03:07,822 --> 00:03:13,448
[SPEAKER_06]: It's important that nobody says or does anything that compromises the integrity of those investigations.

59
00:03:13,749 --> 00:03:15,731
[SPEAKER_06]: You said in the letter, I said things should be done properly.

60
00:03:16,071 --> 00:03:21,617
[SPEAKER_06]: What's proper is to investigate things, to get to the bottom of it, to uncover the truth and then act on those findings.

61
00:03:21,637 --> 00:03:22,618
[SPEAKER_06]: That's exactly

62
00:03:22,598 --> 00:03:23,559
[SPEAKER_06]: what we are doing.

63
00:03:23,780 --> 00:03:26,723
[SPEAKER_06]: So, in parallel, we have been conducting internal inquiries.

64
00:03:26,743 --> 00:03:28,165
[SPEAKER_06]: These are very sensitive matters.

65
00:03:28,185 --> 00:03:33,192
[SPEAKER_06]: They have to be done in a way that doesn't compromise the integrity of police and other investigations.

66
00:03:33,212 --> 00:03:44,066
[SPEAKER_06]: But I've been crystal clear, if anyone has broken the rules, not upheld the standards that I would expect, then they will be held to account, they should face the full consequences of the law, and they will be booted out of the Conservative Party.

67
00:03:44,086 --> 00:03:47,110
[SPEAKER_07]: Can you see what this looks like to readers, to voters, to the public?

68
00:03:47,130 --> 00:03:48,672
[SPEAKER_07]: It looks like the last days of Rome.

69
00:03:48,712 --> 00:03:50,935
[SPEAKER_07]: It's nicking the candlesticks on the way out, isn't it?

70
00:03:50,915 --> 00:03:55,806
[SPEAKER_07]: It just sums up everything that's kind of gone wrong with your government and 14 years of Tory government.

71
00:03:56,588 --> 00:04:04,907
[SPEAKER_07]: The first instinct that the people running your election campaign had, as soon as they found out about it, was to fill their boots.

72
00:04:05,613 --> 00:04:08,175
[SPEAKER_06]: Harry, as I said, I share absolutely in people's...

73
00:04:08,195 --> 00:04:10,437
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm as angry as anybody when I learn about these things.

74
00:04:10,798 --> 00:04:11,418
[SPEAKER_06]: Of course I am.

75
00:04:11,438 --> 00:04:12,980
[SPEAKER_06]: I think the voters are probably angrier.

76
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:15,922
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, well, no, I'm incredibly angry about this.

77
00:04:16,183 --> 00:04:23,409
[SPEAKER_06]: And the right thing to do, and, again, you talked about that letter, to do things properly is to get to the bottom of what happened, to investigate things thoroughly.

78
00:04:23,449 --> 00:04:29,194
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, we have to do that separately to the Gambling Commission, who don't report to me, I don't have the details of their investigation.

79
00:04:29,495 --> 00:04:35,620
[SPEAKER_06]: We have to do that sensitively and carefully so that we don't compromise the integrity of a police and other investigations.

80
00:04:35,600 --> 00:04:41,310
[SPEAKER_06]: But let me be clear, if we come across findings or information that warrants it, we will not hesitate to act.

81
00:04:41,410 --> 00:04:43,574
[SPEAKER_06]: I've been crystal clear that I will hold people to account.

82
00:04:43,594 --> 00:04:44,135
[SPEAKER_06]: Whoever they are.

83
00:04:44,155 --> 00:04:45,597
[SPEAKER_06]: I will kick any... Whoever they are.

84
00:04:46,258 --> 00:04:53,972
[SPEAKER_06]: If anyone has not upheld the standards that I expect, if they have broken the rules, they should face the full consequences of the law and they will be booted out of the Conservative Party.

85
00:04:54,032 --> 00:04:55,314
[SPEAKER_06]: I couldn't be clearer about that.

86
00:04:55,635 --> 00:05:00,443
[SPEAKER_07]: One thing that's very obvious about this election campaign is there is a level of frustration and anger.

87
00:05:00,423 --> 00:05:03,088
[SPEAKER_07]: felt by the voting public to the Conservative Party.

88
00:05:03,108 --> 00:05:08,377
[SPEAKER_07]: You've spoken about it yourself, and you've said that mistakes have been made, and you understand people's frustrations.

89
00:05:09,138 --> 00:05:13,265
[SPEAKER_07]: What mistakes stick out for you, and what frustrations do you think are justified?

90
00:05:13,465 --> 00:05:19,375
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, look, I'm out and about across the country all the time, and I very much sense people's frustrations.

91
00:05:19,716 --> 00:05:25,165
[SPEAKER_06]: Frustrations with me, with the party, and just generally, it's been a very difficult few years.

92
00:05:25,145 --> 00:05:27,270
[SPEAKER_06]: We've had Covid, we have to recover from that.

93
00:05:27,311 --> 00:05:29,737
[SPEAKER_06]: Then we had a war in Ukraine, the impact on people's bills.

94
00:05:29,957 --> 00:05:31,982
[SPEAKER_06]: Of course it hasn't been easy for anyone.

95
00:05:32,243 --> 00:05:36,394
[SPEAKER_06]: And I actually got this job as a result of something that was a mistake.

96
00:05:36,734 --> 00:05:40,504
[SPEAKER_06]: I was very clear about it on the first day I came into this office.

97
00:05:40,484 --> 00:05:46,258
[SPEAKER_06]: when I acknowledge those mistakes, and I was here partly to bring back economic stability, and I'm glad that we've done that.

98
00:05:46,820 --> 00:05:48,985
[SPEAKER_06]: But the key now at this election is about the future.

99
00:05:49,907 --> 00:05:57,987
[SPEAKER_06]: As frustrated as people might be, this is not a by-election, this is not a referendum on the past, this is about the future, and the choice for everyone is clear.

100
00:05:57,967 --> 00:06:03,097
[SPEAKER_06]: I want to build on the progress that we've made, keep cutting everyone's taxes, give people more financial security.

101
00:06:03,438 --> 00:06:05,822
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't want their taxes to go up under a future Labour government.

102
00:06:05,863 --> 00:06:10,051
[SPEAKER_06]: I want to crack on and keep reducing migration, get to net zero in a sensible way.

103
00:06:10,071 --> 00:06:14,760
[SPEAKER_06]: These are all things I believe in, all things I want to deliver, and that's the future that I want to be talking about.

104
00:06:14,740 --> 00:06:16,342
[SPEAKER_07]: Do you understand that feeling that people have?

105
00:06:16,422 --> 00:06:18,604
[SPEAKER_07]: It's something we hear time and time again from our readers.

106
00:06:18,644 --> 00:06:19,305
[SPEAKER_07]: Nothing works.

107
00:06:19,645 --> 00:06:26,693
[SPEAKER_07]: We've got rivers full of sewage, schools crumbling concrete, potholes knocking out tyres, and, you know, left, right and centre.

108
00:06:26,713 --> 00:06:29,516
[SPEAKER_07]: 14 years of Tory government, it feels like the country's falling apart.

109
00:06:29,877 --> 00:06:30,558
[SPEAKER_07]: Why is that?

110
00:06:30,578 --> 00:06:38,486
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, look, of course it's been difficult the last few years, and that's made everything a bit more challenging, particularly the NHS, which I'm sure we'll come on to.

111
00:06:38,787 --> 00:06:40,849
[SPEAKER_06]: But I also... Look, I'm not...

112
00:06:40,829 --> 00:06:48,119
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm not, for one second, taking away from the things that you're saying, but I don't think it's right to say that we haven't made progress in 14 years.

113
00:06:48,179 --> 00:06:49,481
[SPEAKER_06]: I simply don't believe that.

114
00:06:49,521 --> 00:06:53,127
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, of course, that's what the Labour Party are going to say, but I'll just give you one example.

115
00:06:53,527 --> 00:06:54,248
[SPEAKER_06]: Just one example.

116
00:06:54,368 --> 00:06:59,996
[SPEAKER_06]: I think education, schools, is probably the most important thing a government can do to transform people's lives.

117
00:07:00,016 --> 00:07:02,620
[SPEAKER_06]: It's to provide every young person with a phenomenal education.

118
00:07:02,660 --> 00:07:09,570
[SPEAKER_06]: And if you look at 14 years, what Conservatives have done, we've ensured that our schoolchildren in this country, in England,

119
00:07:09,550 --> 00:07:14,334
[SPEAKER_06]: are not just the best readers in the United Kingdom, they're the best readers in the Western world.

120
00:07:14,755 --> 00:07:19,159
[SPEAKER_06]: We've marched up all the international rankings for how well our schoolchildren are performing.

121
00:07:19,419 --> 00:07:25,104
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, that's as a result of Conservative reforms, done painstakingly over years, all opposed by the Labour Party.

122
00:07:25,324 --> 00:07:27,967
[SPEAKER_06]: That's transforming millions of young people's lives.

123
00:07:28,167 --> 00:07:29,488
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's just one thing I can point to.

124
00:07:29,508 --> 00:07:31,670
[SPEAKER_06]: So, yes, of course not everything is perfect.

125
00:07:31,750 --> 00:07:39,557
[SPEAKER_06]: Of course we haven't made as much progress as we would have liked to in some areas, but it's just simply not right to say that the record of the last 14 years is one where we haven't made

126
00:07:39,537 --> 00:07:40,078
[SPEAKER_06]: progress.

127
00:07:40,278 --> 00:07:45,528
[SPEAKER_07]: One thing we can, you know, 14 years is a long time you're in power for two or three of those, we'll give you that.

128
00:07:45,648 --> 00:07:48,894
[SPEAKER_07]: But one graph on your watch, and we've talked about this before, you know what I'm going to say.

129
00:07:49,275 --> 00:07:53,763
[SPEAKER_07]: One graph on your watch that's going the wrong way consistently is your pledge to stop the boats.

130
00:07:53,784 --> 00:07:56,869
[SPEAKER_07]: Since you made that pledge, 50,000 people have crossed the Channel.

131
00:07:56,889 --> 00:08:02,119
[SPEAKER_07]: It is clear and unambiguously going the wrong way for you.

132
00:08:02,099 --> 00:08:11,134
[SPEAKER_07]: I've asked you this before, and do you yet regret making that pledge of stop the boats, which was just so clearly impossible to do?

133
00:08:11,355 --> 00:08:13,899
[SPEAKER_06]: No, because I want people to know where I stand.

134
00:08:14,280 --> 00:08:16,043
[SPEAKER_06]: I think illegal migration is unfair.

135
00:08:16,443 --> 00:08:21,272
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't think it's right that people come to our country illegally, and I want to do everything I can to stop it.

136
00:08:21,312 --> 00:08:24,377
[SPEAKER_06]: And you say that the progress we've made, let's be clear,

137
00:08:24,357 --> 00:08:29,245
[SPEAKER_06]: over the last 12 months, the numbers are lower than they were in the 12 months before.

138
00:08:29,265 --> 00:08:30,267
[SPEAKER_06]: 18% higher this year already.

139
00:08:30,327 --> 00:08:33,572
[SPEAKER_06]: We are halfway through the year now.

140
00:08:34,153 --> 00:08:37,399
[SPEAKER_06]: If you look at a full year, it is down on the year before.

141
00:08:37,459 --> 00:08:39,382
[SPEAKER_06]: I am being clear, we have not got the job done.

142
00:08:39,442 --> 00:08:46,815
[SPEAKER_06]: The only way to do that is to make sure we make it clear to everyone, if you come to our country illegally, you will not get to stay, you will be removed.

143
00:08:47,095 --> 00:08:48,778
[SPEAKER_06]: If I am your Prime Minister,

144
00:08:48,826 --> 00:08:49,787
[SPEAKER_06]: The flights will go to Rwanda.

145
00:08:49,807 --> 00:08:50,207
[SPEAKER_06]: Will they go?

146
00:08:50,227 --> 00:08:51,188
[SPEAKER_06]: People will be removed.

147
00:08:51,248 --> 00:08:51,849
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, they will.

148
00:08:52,129 --> 00:08:52,229
[SPEAKER_06]: When?

149
00:08:52,249 --> 00:08:53,851
[SPEAKER_06]: And the choice for everyone...

150
00:08:53,871 --> 00:08:54,612
[SPEAKER_06]: They'll go in July.

151
00:08:54,712 --> 00:08:57,875
[SPEAKER_06]: And the choice for everyone, the choice for all of you at the election, is about the future.

152
00:08:58,335 --> 00:09:08,465
[SPEAKER_06]: Either you believe illegal migrants should not be in our country, they should be removed to somewhere else, or, with Keir Starmer, they're all going to be released, all the people we've detained, and they'll be out on the streets.

153
00:09:08,585 --> 00:09:09,806
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's the choice for everyone.

154
00:09:10,026 --> 00:09:14,871
[SPEAKER_06]: Do you want illegal migrants on planes going elsewhere, or do you want illegal migrants out on your streets with Labour?

155
00:09:15,011 --> 00:09:16,993
[SPEAKER_06]: That is the choice facing everyone at this election.

156
00:09:16,973 --> 00:09:20,538
[SPEAKER_07]: We're going to open up to the floor in a moment, but there's a huge amount of scepticism about your Rwanda plan.

157
00:09:20,578 --> 00:09:24,924
[SPEAKER_07]: If you were so confident in doing it, why did you call an early election before the flights were taking off?

158
00:09:24,944 --> 00:09:36,721
[SPEAKER_07]: I've been told by several sources, both legal and in Whitehall, that shortly before you called the election, you were told that the prospect of flights taking off in July was going to be severely hindered by massive amounts of legal action.

159
00:09:36,901 --> 00:09:39,364
[SPEAKER_07]: Is that part of the reason that you decided to go early?

160
00:09:39,384 --> 00:09:41,527
[SPEAKER_07]: People have tried to frustrate this, starting with the Labour...

161
00:09:41,547 --> 00:09:42,789
[SPEAKER_06]: But quite successfully, right?

162
00:09:42,849 --> 00:09:43,730
[SPEAKER_07]: ..for a long time.

163
00:09:43,790 --> 00:09:45,613
[SPEAKER_07]: That's why people don't believe the flights are going to go.

164
00:09:45,593 --> 00:09:46,375
[SPEAKER_06]: And what have I done?

165
00:09:46,415 --> 00:09:49,280
[SPEAKER_06]: Every time when someone has tried to block it, I've kept going.

166
00:09:50,442 --> 00:09:51,765
[SPEAKER_06]: I've put new laws on the table.

167
00:09:51,805 --> 00:09:52,847
[SPEAKER_06]: We've passed those laws.

168
00:09:53,047 --> 00:09:54,430
[SPEAKER_06]: We've got a deal done with Albania.

169
00:09:54,450 --> 00:09:55,713
[SPEAKER_06]: But this is about the future.

170
00:09:56,093 --> 00:09:56,775
[SPEAKER_06]: I've got a plan.

171
00:09:57,496 --> 00:10:01,524
[SPEAKER_06]: If you think this is an issue, I've not heard from anyone an alternative plan.

172
00:10:01,564 --> 00:10:04,870
[SPEAKER_06]: And by the way, the last time we were having this conversation, what had just happened?

173
00:10:05,271 --> 00:10:07,315
[SPEAKER_06]: 15 other European countries

174
00:10:07,295 --> 00:10:12,100
[SPEAKER_06]: all agreed that our approach of removing people to a safe alternative was the right one.

175
00:10:12,241 --> 00:10:13,722
[SPEAKER_06]: It's the only way you can stop this problem.

176
00:10:14,003 --> 00:10:16,766
[SPEAKER_06]: You've got to remove the incentive for people to come in the first place.

177
00:10:16,826 --> 00:10:23,714
[SPEAKER_06]: That's my plan, that Labour Party are going to release everyone we've detained, leave them out on the streets... Keir Starmer will be here.

178
00:10:23,734 --> 00:10:25,416
[SPEAKER_07]: ..and that is not going to solve this problem.

179
00:10:25,436 --> 00:10:25,736
[SPEAKER_07]: Surely.

180
00:10:25,756 --> 00:10:26,477
[SPEAKER_07]: Let's have a question.

181
00:10:26,517 --> 00:10:30,982
[SPEAKER_07]: Jonathan Taylor, The Sun's Cabinet's Home Secretary.

182
00:10:31,002 --> 00:10:32,864
[SPEAKER_07]: Former detective, what do you have to say to the Prime Minister?

183
00:10:33,064 --> 00:10:33,725
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you, Harry.

184
00:10:33,865 --> 00:10:35,327
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes, Prime Minister,

185
00:10:35,307 --> 00:10:43,243
[SPEAKER_20]: Interesting what you've just said about that, and we know that the election tends to centre around money, expenditure, where you're going to get money from, what cuts you're going to make.

186
00:10:44,346 --> 00:10:52,422
[SPEAKER_20]: And on migration, we know that over 700,000 skilled, necessary migrants now are employed in the UK.

187
00:10:52,925 --> 00:10:57,452
[SPEAKER_20]: But we've also got 4 million people in receipt of health benefits to stay at home.

188
00:10:57,892 --> 00:11:00,156
[SPEAKER_20]: Surely this is sort of financially counterproductive.

189
00:11:00,817 --> 00:11:02,018
[SPEAKER_06]: So, Jon, I completely...

190
00:11:02,038 --> 00:11:02,639
[SPEAKER_06]: It was Jon, wasn't it?

191
00:11:02,659 --> 00:11:02,980
[SPEAKER_06]: Jonathan.

192
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:04,482
[SPEAKER_06]: Jonathan, completely agree with you.

193
00:11:04,842 --> 00:11:08,528
[SPEAKER_06]: We've had a massive spiral in the welfare bill since Covid.

194
00:11:08,808 --> 00:11:10,731
[SPEAKER_06]: It's gone up by 60%.

195
00:11:10,880 --> 00:11:16,328
[SPEAKER_06]: almost 800,000 more people who are of working age are now been signed off sick.

196
00:11:16,348 --> 00:11:17,129
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't think that's right.

197
00:11:17,470 --> 00:11:20,935
[SPEAKER_06]: We were making great progress before the pandemic and we need to get back to that.

198
00:11:21,075 --> 00:11:31,791
[SPEAKER_06]: So we set out a plan to reform the system to do that, have people provide more medical evidence, reform how the sick note, fit note process works because it's not working, make it clear that if you don't accept a job,

199
00:11:31,771 --> 00:11:38,361
[SPEAKER_06]: when your job coach tells you there's a sensible job for you, you won't be able to keep receiving your benefits, all very common sense things.

200
00:11:38,742 --> 00:11:41,526
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's going to help us make savings in our welfare budget.

201
00:11:41,827 --> 00:11:45,172
[SPEAKER_06]: And we can use those to help cut your taxes and support people into work.

202
00:11:45,192 --> 00:11:48,738
[SPEAKER_06]: Because I completely agree with you, everyone who can work should work.

203
00:11:49,119 --> 00:11:50,401
[SPEAKER_06]: Our reforms are going to deliver that.

204
00:11:50,461 --> 00:11:53,205
[SPEAKER_06]: And in contrast, again, because all elections are a choice,

205
00:11:53,185 --> 00:11:54,868
[SPEAKER_06]: What has the Labour Party said?

206
00:11:55,309 --> 00:11:58,795
[SPEAKER_06]: We think we can make savings in a welfare bill that's gone up as much as it has.

207
00:11:58,815 --> 00:12:05,566
[SPEAKER_06]: £69 billion today we spend on people with ill health, disability benefits, a working age.

208
00:12:05,967 --> 00:12:10,114
[SPEAKER_06]: The Labour Party think that you can't make one penny of savings from that bill.

209
00:12:10,094 --> 00:12:15,281
[SPEAKER_06]: They don't think you can make one penny of savings, and that tells you the choice ahead of you at this election.

210
00:12:15,681 --> 00:12:19,506
[SPEAKER_06]: If you think we can do something about this, we're the only people who are going to do that for you.

211
00:12:19,526 --> 00:12:23,090
[SPEAKER_07]: Prime Minister, the other part of Jonathan's question was about the record rate of legal migration.

212
00:12:23,471 --> 00:12:36,928
[SPEAKER_07]: Do you regret not doing more when people in your own Cabinet, take Isabella Braveman, for example, or Robert Jenrick, were encouraging you to go further and faster on stopping legal, on capping legal migration, two years ago, and now...

213
00:12:36,908 --> 00:12:40,036
[SPEAKER_07]: In your manifesto, you're promising a cap on migration.

214
00:12:40,076 --> 00:12:42,040
[SPEAKER_07]: Why didn't you do it when you had the opportunity to do it?

215
00:12:42,060 --> 00:12:45,008
[SPEAKER_06]: So we got on and delivered lower migration.

216
00:12:45,028 --> 00:12:47,895
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm not going to defend the levels that I inherited, because they were just too high.

217
00:12:48,095 --> 00:12:48,396
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

218
00:12:48,416 --> 00:12:50,060
[SPEAKER_06]: But you could have done more earlier, right?

219
00:12:50,080 --> 00:12:50,461
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, hang on.

220
00:12:50,581 --> 00:12:53,027
[SPEAKER_06]: Again, I've been Prime Minister for 18 months.

221
00:12:53,007 --> 00:12:59,939
[SPEAKER_06]: Numbers were down last year, and this year, the number of visas that we issued for all the key categories were down by 30%.

222
00:13:00,159 --> 00:13:08,434
[SPEAKER_06]: If you look at the forecast, independent forecast, not mine, we're forecast to halve net migration in 12 months because of the measures that I've already taken.

223
00:13:08,795 --> 00:13:10,638
[SPEAKER_06]: By the way, the Labour Party opposed all of those.

224
00:13:11,099 --> 00:13:12,501
[SPEAKER_06]: And I want to go further.

225
00:13:12,481 --> 00:13:17,366
[SPEAKER_06]: So I want to give all of you the certainty that it's going to keep coming down year after year, and that's why we're going to have...

226
00:13:17,386 --> 00:13:21,671
[SPEAKER_06]: But it would have been coming down... ..a legal cap voted on in Parliament every year to guarantee that the numbers keep coming down.

227
00:13:21,691 --> 00:13:23,133
[SPEAKER_06]: Prime Minister, why didn't you do it when you had the chance?

228
00:13:23,153 --> 00:13:26,476
[SPEAKER_06]: And, as Jonathan says, reform the welfare system and get people into work instead.

229
00:13:26,496 --> 00:13:27,878
[SPEAKER_06]: That is the right approach for our country.

230
00:13:27,898 --> 00:13:30,421
[SPEAKER_06]: If it's the right approach for our country, why didn't you do it 18 months ago?

231
00:13:30,441 --> 00:13:31,602
[SPEAKER_06]: Because we've got the numbers down.

232
00:13:31,622 --> 00:13:34,766
[SPEAKER_06]: We passed new rules that have kicked in to bring the numbers down.

233
00:13:34,786 --> 00:13:39,791
[SPEAKER_07]: Not in any meaningful way compared to the 745,000 people that came last year.

234
00:13:39,811 --> 00:13:40,712
[SPEAKER_06]: Harry, let migration leave.

235
00:13:40,732 --> 00:13:42,454
[SPEAKER_06]: Can you name me a single other year

236
00:13:42,991 --> 00:13:46,167
[SPEAKER_06]: ever where we have reduced the number of visas by 30%.

237
00:13:46,383 --> 00:13:50,447
[SPEAKER_06]: These numbers are on your watch, but it's clear that you were coming into slightly late to this.

238
00:13:50,467 --> 00:13:52,248
[SPEAKER_06]: No, you just said... You just said...

239
00:13:52,609 --> 00:13:54,871
[SPEAKER_06]: So, whose fault is it that it's so high?

240
00:13:54,991 --> 00:13:56,592
[SPEAKER_06]: I've been Prime Minister for 18 months.

241
00:13:56,612 --> 00:13:57,533
[SPEAKER_06]: So, Lestrade's fault?

242
00:13:57,553 --> 00:13:58,334
[SPEAKER_06]: Was it Boris's fault?

243
00:13:58,534 --> 00:13:59,995
[SPEAKER_06]: The numbers were too high.

244
00:14:00,336 --> 00:14:00,916
[SPEAKER_06]: Whose fault was it?

245
00:14:01,116 --> 00:14:02,578
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, the numbers were too high.

246
00:14:02,958 --> 00:14:03,498
[SPEAKER_06]: Oh, go on.

247
00:14:03,619 --> 00:14:04,940
[SPEAKER_06]: If it's not your fault, whose fault was it?

248
00:14:04,960 --> 00:14:05,140
[SPEAKER_06]: Hang on.

249
00:14:05,760 --> 00:14:07,922
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, obviously, the numbers are too high.

250
00:14:07,962 --> 00:14:10,144
[SPEAKER_06]: I've got the job and I've brought them down.

251
00:14:10,184 --> 00:14:16,390
[SPEAKER_06]: And you just said, oh, no, you haven't done very much, and said, tell me another year where someone has reduced the number of visas issued by 30%.

252
00:14:16,370 --> 00:14:19,596
[SPEAKER_06]: Never happened in our country before, because I took strict action.

253
00:14:19,716 --> 00:14:20,618
[SPEAKER_06]: I'll give you one example.

254
00:14:20,898 --> 00:14:24,645
[SPEAKER_06]: We raised the salary that you need to earn to be able to come here to work to £38,500.

255
00:14:26,268 --> 00:14:32,640
[SPEAKER_06]: We've made the very reasonable point that actually if you're going to bring your family dependents to this country, you should be able to support them.

256
00:14:32,620 --> 00:14:36,046
[SPEAKER_06]: Economically, again, I think that's a relatively common-sense, reasonable approach.

257
00:14:36,366 --> 00:14:41,354
[SPEAKER_06]: We've tightened up the social care visa, the student visa, where people were bringing lots of dependents to our country.

258
00:14:41,695 --> 00:14:42,496
[SPEAKER_06]: They weren't working.

259
00:14:42,737 --> 00:14:43,838
[SPEAKER_06]: They weren't accounted for.

260
00:14:44,199 --> 00:14:45,181
[SPEAKER_06]: I made all those changes.

261
00:14:45,421 --> 00:14:49,007
[SPEAKER_06]: The numbers are forecast to halve in 12 months as a result of them, right?

262
00:14:49,368 --> 00:14:53,815
[SPEAKER_06]: And I want to go further with a legal cap and give you the guarantee that they will keep coming down.

263
00:14:53,935 --> 00:14:58,122
[SPEAKER_06]: Again, the choice for you at this election is everything that I've just said,

264
00:14:58,102 --> 00:15:06,917
[SPEAKER_06]: or a Labour party that opposed all of those things, no cap, and Keir Starmer, who, back in the day when he was running to be leader, said he wanted to bring back free movement of people.

265
00:15:07,437 --> 00:15:11,584
[SPEAKER_07]: Right, Keir Starmer will be here shortly, and I'm sure we're going to talk about that.

266
00:15:11,945 --> 00:15:14,209
[SPEAKER_07]: Let's open up and change to a different direction.

267
00:15:14,870 --> 00:15:16,032
[SPEAKER_07]: Where's Fliss, Miss Gilbert?

268
00:15:16,152 --> 00:15:17,494
[SPEAKER_07]: Fliss, your question to the Prime Minister.

269
00:15:17,474 --> 00:15:17,714
[SPEAKER_15]: Hiya.

270
00:15:18,716 --> 00:15:25,565
[SPEAKER_15]: So my dad passed away six weeks ago yesterday due to a massive failure from the NHS.

271
00:15:25,966 --> 00:15:27,808
[SPEAKER_15]: I believe the NHS is broken.

272
00:15:28,329 --> 00:15:35,799
[SPEAKER_15]: We waited nine months for a cancer diagnosis and a further nine months for a metastatic cancer diagnosis.

273
00:15:36,300 --> 00:15:39,364
[SPEAKER_15]: Before we got the diagnosis, he passed away.

274
00:15:39,344 --> 00:15:41,427
[SPEAKER_15]: There was no treatment, no nothing.

275
00:15:42,189 --> 00:15:43,731
[SPEAKER_15]: We feel like we've been let down.

276
00:15:43,771 --> 00:15:47,397
[SPEAKER_15]: We feel like there are many more families that are struggling.

277
00:15:47,498 --> 00:15:49,220
[SPEAKER_15]: We've been through 18 months of hell.

278
00:15:49,841 --> 00:15:53,407
[SPEAKER_15]: What are you going to do to stop people suffering like we've had to?

279
00:15:53,628 --> 00:15:56,172
[SPEAKER_15]: What are your pledges for the NHS?

280
00:15:56,573 --> 00:15:57,054
[SPEAKER_06]: Prime Minister.

281
00:15:57,154 --> 00:16:07,526
[SPEAKER_06]: Fliss, I'm so sorry to hear about your dad and if you let me know afterwards which trust it was, I'll make sure that we look into it and someone gets in touch with you so we can find out what went wrong.

282
00:16:07,987 --> 00:16:10,770
[SPEAKER_06]: I can't imagine how difficult that's been for you and your family.

283
00:16:10,791 --> 00:16:13,574
[SPEAKER_06]: I think as probably most of you know, I grew up in an NHS family.

284
00:16:13,634 --> 00:16:15,096
[SPEAKER_06]: I know how important healthcare is.

285
00:16:15,176 --> 00:16:19,341
[SPEAKER_06]: I've worked for my mum in the pharmacy, helping people myself.

286
00:16:19,321 --> 00:16:27,973
[SPEAKER_06]: When it comes to cancer, the most important thing we can do is, as you highlighted, just diagnose it as soon as possible.

287
00:16:28,353 --> 00:16:33,500
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's the best chance we've got of helping someone, getting them the treatment they need and make sure that they survive.

288
00:16:34,021 --> 00:16:38,147
[SPEAKER_06]: And one of the ways we're doing that is by rolling out things called community diagnostic centres.

289
00:16:38,447 --> 00:16:42,152
[SPEAKER_06]: So we've done 160, and if we're re-elected, we'll do many more.

290
00:16:42,473 --> 00:16:47,860
[SPEAKER_06]: And these are units in your local community where you can get all your checks, tests and scans done.

291
00:16:47,840 --> 00:16:50,344
[SPEAKER_06]: and that way get your diagnosis much quicker.

292
00:16:50,724 --> 00:16:56,292
[SPEAKER_06]: We're hiring more oncologists, we're using technology as well and new forms of testing to identify things.

293
00:16:56,893 --> 00:16:59,937
[SPEAKER_06]: But fundamentally, what happened to you and your family isn't acceptable.

294
00:17:00,618 --> 00:17:02,380
[SPEAKER_06]: And I can only apologise.

295
00:17:03,041 --> 00:17:05,785
[SPEAKER_06]: You know the challenges we're dealing with with COVID.

296
00:17:06,246 --> 00:17:09,190
[SPEAKER_06]: Cancer in particular was one where for two years,

297
00:17:09,507 --> 00:17:17,140
[SPEAKER_06]: lots of people didn't present with symptoms and we're catching up with that now and that's an awful tragedy, one of the many tragedies of Covid.

298
00:17:17,721 --> 00:17:27,778
[SPEAKER_06]: The key thing now is to just keep working through the backlog and as I said more oncologists, more community diagnostic centres and new technology is going to help us build on what we're doing which is improving the survival rates.

299
00:17:28,119 --> 00:17:30,182
[SPEAKER_07]: Bliss has that allayed some of your concerns?

300
00:17:30,449 --> 00:17:31,330
[SPEAKER_15]: Not really.

301
00:17:32,091 --> 00:17:43,385
[SPEAKER_15]: My dad, we actually referred him in the January and it was the August that he, I actually took him myself to hospital and I said, we cannot go through any more of this.

302
00:17:43,425 --> 00:17:46,469
[SPEAKER_15]: He's lost nearly eight stone in weight, other symptoms.

303
00:17:47,129 --> 00:17:48,211
[SPEAKER_15]: I am not moving.

304
00:17:48,391 --> 00:17:49,352
[SPEAKER_15]: I said, I'm so sorry.

305
00:17:49,392 --> 00:17:54,218
[SPEAKER_15]: I know you're under pressure, but I am not moving until you take this seriously and you deal with my dad.

306
00:17:54,578 --> 00:17:58,363
[SPEAKER_15]: And within a week, he was in, operated on,

307
00:17:58,343 --> 00:18:00,828
[SPEAKER_15]: bits removed that were cancerous.

308
00:18:01,389 --> 00:18:02,291
[SPEAKER_15]: So, yeah.

309
00:18:02,492 --> 00:18:07,542
[SPEAKER_07]: Prime Minister, we have readers sending in questions like this by the bucket load, I'm afraid.

310
00:18:07,683 --> 00:18:09,286
[SPEAKER_07]: It's a real feeling.

311
00:18:09,306 --> 00:18:10,288
[SPEAKER_07]: What has gone wrong on your watch?

312
00:18:10,308 --> 00:18:14,557
[SPEAKER_07]: I know, obviously, the pandemic, but, you know, the buck does have to stop somewhere.

313
00:18:14,617 --> 00:18:16,401
[SPEAKER_07]: And again, whose fault is this?

314
00:18:16,541 --> 00:18:18,445
[SPEAKER_07]: And what can you do to turn this around?

315
00:18:18,425 --> 00:18:19,487
[SPEAKER_06]: in any meaningful way?

316
00:18:19,507 --> 00:18:23,433
[SPEAKER_06]: Obviously, it's my responsibility, because I'm the one in charge, and I've been very clear.

317
00:18:23,453 --> 00:18:26,277
[SPEAKER_06]: We haven't made as much progress on waiting lists as I would have liked.

318
00:18:26,297 --> 00:18:27,719
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, you talked about the pandemic.

319
00:18:27,739 --> 00:18:31,044
[SPEAKER_06]: It's, I think, important for everyone to just understand the scale of what happened.

320
00:18:31,565 --> 00:18:38,475
[SPEAKER_06]: During the Covid years, six million referrals that normally would have happened didn't happen.

321
00:18:38,495 --> 00:18:40,298
[SPEAKER_06]: Just think about that, six million.

322
00:18:41,172 --> 00:18:48,021
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, the NHS today, because of the money we've put in, the doctors and nurses we've hired, is doing more than it's ever done.

323
00:18:48,462 --> 00:18:53,909
[SPEAKER_06]: It's working flat out, the amount of treatments, checks, test stands, operations, all of that is at record levels.

324
00:18:54,489 --> 00:19:04,142
[SPEAKER_06]: But obviously, it is just a challenge to work through the fact that we've got this six million missed referrals that obviously now are coming into the system and we're catching up on.

325
00:19:04,122 --> 00:19:05,684
[SPEAKER_06]: and it's going to take time to work through that.

326
00:19:05,724 --> 00:19:13,335
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm not going to pretend it can be fixed overnight, but I can assure you that the NHS budget will continue to increase ahead of inflation in the next Parliament.

327
00:19:13,355 --> 00:19:14,517
[SPEAKER_06]: It's already at record levels.

328
00:19:14,957 --> 00:19:22,207
[SPEAKER_06]: We've got more doctors and nurses, and we're hiring more, and we're using new technology and new innovations to get you the health care that you need.

329
00:19:22,267 --> 00:19:29,117
[SPEAKER_06]: So we're doing all the right things, but when you've had six million referrals that were missed and are going to take time to come back, it's just going to take a bit of time.

330
00:19:30,127 --> 00:19:30,708
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Phyllis.

331
00:19:30,728 --> 00:19:31,509
[SPEAKER_07]: Let's move on.

332
00:19:31,529 --> 00:19:32,211
[SPEAKER_07]: Is Rehan here?

333
00:19:32,451 --> 00:19:33,413
[SPEAKER_07]: A question for Rehan.

334
00:19:33,433 --> 00:19:33,493
[SPEAKER_05]: Hi.

335
00:19:33,513 --> 00:19:34,515
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you, Harry.

336
00:19:34,535 --> 00:19:35,176
[SPEAKER_05]: Hi, Prime Minister.

337
00:19:35,677 --> 00:19:40,164
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm a student about to enter the world of work and I'm deeply worried about the housing crisis.

338
00:19:40,645 --> 00:19:45,874
[SPEAKER_05]: Can you look me in the eye and tell me that you are comfortable with young people being forced to rent until they're in their 40s?

339
00:19:46,951 --> 00:19:48,373
[SPEAKER_06]: No, of course I'm not.

340
00:19:48,974 --> 00:19:52,158
[SPEAKER_06]: I want you to own your own home, because it's an incredibly special thing.

341
00:19:52,378 --> 00:19:53,239
[SPEAKER_06]: I remember what it felt like.

342
00:19:53,259 --> 00:20:01,389
[SPEAKER_06]: I want everyone to feel like that, because owning your own home is part of what allows you to build a life, build a family, and gives you a stake in your community.

343
00:20:01,449 --> 00:20:04,053
[SPEAKER_06]: It's something I passionately believe, and I want to make it easier for you.

344
00:20:04,133 --> 00:20:09,640
[SPEAKER_06]: I'll tell you two very specific things that I will do for you and everyone else if I'm your prime minister on July 5th.

345
00:20:10,180 --> 00:20:14,005
[SPEAKER_06]: One is to reintroduce a new form of help to buy.

346
00:20:13,985 --> 00:20:16,749
[SPEAKER_06]: which means you won't have to save up as much for the deposit.

347
00:20:16,809 --> 00:20:18,772
[SPEAKER_06]: It will save you tens of thousands of pounds.

348
00:20:18,812 --> 00:20:22,557
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's a big issue, waiting till you're 40 to save up for the deposit.

349
00:20:22,757 --> 00:20:23,979
[SPEAKER_06]: It will help solve that problem.

350
00:20:24,219 --> 00:20:29,046
[SPEAKER_06]: And the second thing we're going to do is abolish stamp duty for first-time buyers, effectively.

351
00:20:29,567 --> 00:20:31,730
[SPEAKER_06]: There'll be a cap, but most people will be covered by it.

352
00:20:31,930 --> 00:20:36,656
[SPEAKER_06]: And then again, that's going to save you thousands of pounds, and it's going to get you on the housing ladder far quicker.

353
00:20:37,037 --> 00:20:42,945
[SPEAKER_06]: Because the challenge that I see when I talk to everyone of your age is, actually, they could probably afford the mortgage.

354
00:20:42,925 --> 00:20:47,073
[SPEAKER_06]: The challenge, I can see you nodding, the challenge is how long will it take me to save up the deposit?

355
00:20:47,493 --> 00:20:54,246
[SPEAKER_06]: And the combination of a new help to buy and actually abolishing stamp duty means that you'll be able to get on the housing ladder far quicker.

356
00:20:54,306 --> 00:20:57,211
[SPEAKER_06]: So it's two very specific things so you can own your own home.

357
00:20:57,271 --> 00:21:02,721
[SPEAKER_06]: And again, I'll point this out, because all elections are a choice, the Labour Party have said no to both of those things.

358
00:21:03,122 --> 00:21:05,406
[SPEAKER_06]: So you're only going to get those things if I'm your Prime Minister.

359
00:21:05,723 --> 00:21:07,747
[SPEAKER_07]: Talking of homeowners, is Linda here?

360
00:21:07,767 --> 00:21:09,451
[SPEAKER_07]: A question about mortgages, I think.

361
00:21:09,471 --> 00:21:09,711
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

362
00:21:10,252 --> 00:21:11,435
[SPEAKER_14]: Good evening, Mr Sooner.

363
00:21:11,555 --> 00:21:11,916
[SPEAKER_07]: Hi, Linda.

364
00:21:12,517 --> 00:21:19,992
[SPEAKER_14]: How do you feel about the very many people with mortgages struggling to pay bills or who have lost their homes because of the hike in the interest rates?

365
00:21:20,473 --> 00:21:21,455
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

366
00:21:21,475 --> 00:21:24,422
[SPEAKER_06]: Linda, look, we talked about it right at the beginning of this interview.

367
00:21:24,722 --> 00:21:27,107
[SPEAKER_06]: That was my number one priority when I got this job.

368
00:21:27,442 --> 00:21:29,464
[SPEAKER_06]: Interest rates are at a very high level.

369
00:21:29,604 --> 00:21:30,886
[SPEAKER_06]: And why were they at a high level?

370
00:21:30,926 --> 00:21:32,187
[SPEAKER_06]: Because inflation was at 11%.

371
00:21:32,447 --> 00:21:35,371
[SPEAKER_06]: I haven't experienced anything like that in this country for decades.

372
00:21:35,631 --> 00:21:42,138
[SPEAKER_06]: That's why I made it my number one priority to bring inflation down, because that's what will then allow interest rates to come down.

373
00:21:42,598 --> 00:21:48,385
[SPEAKER_06]: And as you've seen, inflation just got back to target just last week, which is very, very promising news.

374
00:21:48,425 --> 00:21:53,790
[SPEAKER_06]: You heard from the Bank of England, so we're now on track to start seeing interest rates and mortgage rates be cut.

375
00:21:54,111 --> 00:21:56,233
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's how I give you financial security.

376
00:21:56,213 --> 00:22:05,920
[SPEAKER_14]: How's that going to help the people who have lost their homes because the interest rate rises have gone so high they can't keep up with their bills, not just their mortgages but regular bills?

377
00:22:06,203 --> 00:22:13,173
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, all of this is about giving you financial security, which is why I want to keep cutting people's taxes so they have more money in their pockets at the end of every month.

378
00:22:13,513 --> 00:22:17,779
[SPEAKER_06]: Now that we've got the economy in a better place, we started that at the end of last year.

379
00:22:17,799 --> 00:22:23,467
[SPEAKER_06]: So this year, everyone in work is getting a tax cut that's worth about £900 on average.

380
00:22:23,507 --> 00:22:27,372
[SPEAKER_06]: So that will really help people with their bills as well as inflation coming down.

381
00:22:27,673 --> 00:22:29,916
[SPEAKER_06]: And if I'm re-elected, we're going to go further.

382
00:22:29,896 --> 00:22:32,562
[SPEAKER_06]: And we're going to keep cutting your taxes at every stage in your life.

383
00:22:32,623 --> 00:22:35,048
[SPEAKER_06]: So if you're in work, you'll keep getting more tax cuts.

384
00:22:35,369 --> 00:22:39,439
[SPEAKER_06]: If you're self-employed, we're going to abolish national insurance, self-employed people.

385
00:22:39,659 --> 00:22:44,331
[SPEAKER_06]: So all of that is going to put more money in everyone's bank account, give you financial security.

386
00:22:44,772 --> 00:22:46,977
[SPEAKER_06]: But crucially, again, this is a choice.

387
00:22:46,957 --> 00:22:48,299
[SPEAKER_06]: This election is a choice.

388
00:22:48,600 --> 00:22:57,133
[SPEAKER_06]: We can build on the progress we've made, keep cutting taxes, or as I've been pointing out, if Keir Starmer is your Prime Minister, all of you are going to face higher taxes.

389
00:22:57,173 --> 00:23:04,283
[SPEAKER_06]: That is not going to help anyone with any of the bills, Linda, that you're talking about if the Labour Party is taking more tax out of your bank account every month.

390
00:23:04,303 --> 00:23:08,610
[SPEAKER_14]: With respect, could I just say, it's not just the bills.

391
00:23:08,590 --> 00:23:13,658
[SPEAKER_14]: for regular everyday living.

392
00:23:14,159 --> 00:23:16,502
[SPEAKER_14]: It's keeping a roof above your head.

393
00:23:17,223 --> 00:23:22,772
[SPEAKER_14]: In the first quarter of this year, upwards of 97,000 people were in arrears with their mortgage.

394
00:23:22,792 --> 00:23:26,818
[SPEAKER_14]: That's getting on for 100,000 people who could potentially be on the streets.

395
00:23:27,406 --> 00:23:33,998
[SPEAKER_06]: So to help people with mortgages, if you go and talk to your bank, what we put in place is a mortgage charter that covers the industry.

396
00:23:34,358 --> 00:23:44,436
[SPEAKER_06]: So if you talk to your bank, what we've organized is for you to be able to get a holiday on your mortgage, move to an interest-only mortgage, stretch out the term,

397
00:23:44,416 --> 00:23:47,140
[SPEAKER_06]: All of that you can do without affecting your credit rating.

398
00:23:47,261 --> 00:23:56,436
[SPEAKER_06]: It can save you potentially hundreds of pounds a month in mortgage costs, which is really practical support, and your bank has to do that all for you if you like it.

399
00:23:56,476 --> 00:23:58,639
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's the solution that we've put in place.

400
00:23:58,920 --> 00:24:09,697
[SPEAKER_06]: The combination of those things, extending your term, moving to interest only, those types of things will save you hundreds of pounds, enable you to keep your house, and the bank can't repossess your house.

401
00:24:09,817 --> 00:24:10,879
[SPEAKER_06]: We've made that clear.

402
00:24:10,859 --> 00:24:15,166
[SPEAKER_06]: for a very prolonged period of time after you first told them that you're struggling.

403
00:24:15,406 --> 00:24:18,010
[SPEAKER_06]: So all of those predictions, we didn't have them in the past.

404
00:24:18,030 --> 00:24:22,056
[SPEAKER_06]: They're new, something that the Chancellor negotiated with all the lenders in our country.

405
00:24:22,277 --> 00:24:23,579
[SPEAKER_06]: So it's called the Mortgage Charter.

406
00:24:23,819 --> 00:24:29,288
[SPEAKER_06]: For anyone struggling with that, please talk to your bank and say that I said that that's what you're entitled to, because that's what you should be able to get.

407
00:24:29,308 --> 00:24:30,690
[SPEAKER_06]: Prime Minister, we're talking about solutions.

408
00:24:30,710 --> 00:24:31,671
[SPEAKER_07]: Let's step back a little bit.

409
00:24:31,771 --> 00:24:38,622
[SPEAKER_07]: I think a lot of the anger that people feel about this Government, do you feel some responsibility for inflicting Liz's trust on the voters?

410
00:24:38,888 --> 00:24:39,349
[SPEAKER_07]: Excuse me?

411
00:24:39,469 --> 00:24:42,634
[SPEAKER_07]: Do you feel any responsibility for inflicting Liz Truss on the voters?

412
00:24:42,674 --> 00:24:44,857
[SPEAKER_06]: Look, we started this interview with that, right?

413
00:24:45,498 --> 00:24:50,126
[SPEAKER_06]: I spent a summer, a couple of summers ago, saying that what Liz Truss was proposing was wrong.

414
00:24:50,907 --> 00:24:54,212
[SPEAKER_06]: And I was behind and everyone said to me, why are you bothering?

415
00:24:54,272 --> 00:24:55,414
[SPEAKER_06]: Why are you still talking about this?

416
00:24:55,474 --> 00:24:56,816
[SPEAKER_06]: No-one wants to hear what you have to say.

417
00:24:56,876 --> 00:24:59,540
[SPEAKER_06]: I kept talking about it every day of that campaign...

418
00:24:59,560 --> 00:25:00,221
[SPEAKER_06]: But why didn't people believe...?

419
00:25:00,241 --> 00:25:02,565
[SPEAKER_06]: ..because I believed in what I was saying, right?

420
00:25:02,645 --> 00:25:05,790
[SPEAKER_06]: And I said very clearly I didn't think that was right for our country.

421
00:25:05,770 --> 00:25:09,817
[SPEAKER_06]: And I was very clear on the first day I got this job that mistakes had been made.

422
00:25:10,178 --> 00:25:12,241
[SPEAKER_06]: I was right then when I warned about Liz Truss.

423
00:25:12,301 --> 00:25:19,113
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's why all of you can trust me now when I also warn about the damage that Keir Starmer would do to our economy.

424
00:25:19,474 --> 00:25:21,858
[SPEAKER_06]: In that election, everyone said I was going to lose.

425
00:25:22,138 --> 00:25:23,841
[SPEAKER_06]: I was saying something that no one wanted to hear.

426
00:25:24,282 --> 00:25:26,125
[SPEAKER_06]: But I was saying it because I believed it.

427
00:25:26,105 --> 00:25:34,741
[SPEAKER_06]: And I'm telling you again now, all seems a bit familiar, if Keir Starmer is your Prime Minister, the economy is going to suffer and all of you are going to suffer.

428
00:25:34,801 --> 00:25:36,084
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't want to see that happen.

429
00:25:36,324 --> 00:25:38,568
[SPEAKER_06]: That's why I'm carrying on going every day in this election.

430
00:25:38,688 --> 00:25:42,155
[SPEAKER_06]: I believe in what I'm saying and I want to stop those tax rises happening for all of you.

431
00:25:42,175 --> 00:25:43,337
[SPEAKER_06]: Do you ever wish you were...

432
00:25:43,553 --> 00:25:54,534
[SPEAKER_07]: Do you ever wish, though, you were still the incredibly popular Chancellor that you were before, you know, serving in the most electorally successful Conservative government since Thatcher?

433
00:25:54,714 --> 00:25:55,215
[SPEAKER_07]: Was it worth it?

434
00:25:56,037 --> 00:25:58,822
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, I'm very proud of what we did in government.

435
00:25:58,842 --> 00:26:01,427
[SPEAKER_06]: I was proud to have served in government, but I can't really

436
00:26:01,407 --> 00:26:04,391
[SPEAKER_07]: Would you do the same... Would you do exactly the same over again?

437
00:26:04,431 --> 00:26:11,541
[SPEAKER_07]: If you had your chance, would you take out Johnson and run the same campaign you ran against Truss and done the same things you've done since then?

438
00:26:11,581 --> 00:26:13,183
[SPEAKER_07]: Or what would you like to change about your time?

439
00:26:13,203 --> 00:26:14,725
[SPEAKER_07]: Harry, I am focused on the future.

440
00:26:14,965 --> 00:26:17,449
[SPEAKER_07]: Ah, but people have a right to know whether you've made...

441
00:26:17,469 --> 00:26:17,569
[SPEAKER_07]: I am.

442
00:26:17,589 --> 00:26:19,712
[SPEAKER_07]: You said you've made mistakes and hear their frustrations.

443
00:26:19,732 --> 00:26:21,875
[SPEAKER_06]: And I am focused on the future, right?

444
00:26:21,895 --> 00:26:30,807
[SPEAKER_06]: Because this election, as I said, of course we can talk about the past and we have done, but for all of you, the choice for you is who do you want to run the country for the next five years?

445
00:26:30,787 --> 00:26:34,653
[SPEAKER_06]: Who is placed to deliver the security that you and your families want?

446
00:26:34,693 --> 00:26:40,262
[SPEAKER_06]: You have to ask yourself, as Kate said in the intro, I don't think any of you can tell me what Labour are going to do if they're in power.

447
00:26:40,883 --> 00:26:44,369
[SPEAKER_06]: And when governments and politicians don't tell you, it's because they think you probably won't like it.

448
00:26:44,990 --> 00:26:47,113
[SPEAKER_06]: And I'm telling you, your taxes are going to go up.

449
00:26:47,193 --> 00:26:48,656
[SPEAKER_06]: It's as simple as that.

450
00:26:48,896 --> 00:26:49,898
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's the choice for you.

451
00:26:49,918 --> 00:26:53,183
[SPEAKER_06]: Can you afford £2,000 worth of tax rises?

452
00:26:53,163 --> 00:26:54,665
[SPEAKER_06]: Can your family, can your loved ones?

453
00:26:54,705 --> 00:26:56,547
[SPEAKER_06]: We heard from Linda about the challenge of bills.

454
00:26:56,887 --> 00:26:59,631
[SPEAKER_06]: Because that's what's coming down the track if Labour are in power.

455
00:26:59,731 --> 00:27:01,453
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's why I want to fight very hard.

456
00:27:01,473 --> 00:27:02,654
[SPEAKER_07]: That's the choice of this election.

457
00:27:02,694 --> 00:27:07,740
[SPEAKER_07]: Last October, you were the one that said there'd been... You attacked in a speech 30 years of failed political consensus.

458
00:27:08,201 --> 00:27:11,004
[SPEAKER_07]: The Tory party have been in power for half of that 30 years.

459
00:27:11,504 --> 00:27:15,389
[SPEAKER_07]: You've opened up the door to your record, to the government's record.

460
00:27:15,970 --> 00:27:17,972
[SPEAKER_07]: It doesn't bear much scrutiny, though, does it?

461
00:27:17,952 --> 00:27:19,894
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, Harry, it really does.

462
00:27:19,934 --> 00:27:23,218
[SPEAKER_06]: Look, you've asked me this for another five years, but you're saying that the last 30 have been a failure.

463
00:27:23,238 --> 00:27:24,320
[SPEAKER_06]: We went over this earlier, right?

464
00:27:24,380 --> 00:27:26,222
[SPEAKER_06]: So I'm not going to pretend that we've got everything right.

465
00:27:26,242 --> 00:27:27,343
[SPEAKER_06]: Of course we didn't, right?

466
00:27:27,563 --> 00:27:28,444
[SPEAKER_06]: No government does.

467
00:27:28,945 --> 00:27:31,488
[SPEAKER_06]: Of course I'd wish we'd made more progress on areas.

468
00:27:31,548 --> 00:27:35,493
[SPEAKER_06]: And I know the last few years have been particularly frustrating, given everything that's happened.

469
00:27:35,833 --> 00:27:39,417
[SPEAKER_06]: But I'm not going to sit here and say that 14 years hasn't made this country a better place.

470
00:27:39,638 --> 00:27:41,800
[SPEAKER_06]: Let's just go back 14 years, what happened.

471
00:27:42,301 --> 00:27:47,487
[SPEAKER_06]: We were left a note by the Labour Party laughing about the fact that there was no money left in this country.

472
00:27:47,467 --> 00:27:49,889
[SPEAKER_06]: They have bankrupted this country, and what have we done since then?

473
00:27:50,330 --> 00:27:54,253
[SPEAKER_06]: We've delivered the third highest growth rate of all the large major economies in the world.

474
00:27:54,594 --> 00:27:56,075
[SPEAKER_06]: We've created 800 jobs a day.

475
00:27:56,295 --> 00:27:57,516
[SPEAKER_06]: We talked about our children.

476
00:27:57,957 --> 00:28:00,299
[SPEAKER_06]: We've halved crime, and there's more to do on all these things.

477
00:28:00,319 --> 00:28:03,282
[SPEAKER_06]: We've increased defence spending so that we can stand tall in the world.

478
00:28:04,062 --> 00:28:05,984
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, I could go on and on and on, right?

479
00:28:06,004 --> 00:28:08,026
[SPEAKER_06]: The point is, that's 14 years.

480
00:28:08,246 --> 00:28:14,352
[SPEAKER_06]: There's lots of things that would have made a difference to you, some things you would have wished we'd have done differently, but this election is about the future.

481
00:28:14,332 --> 00:28:29,546
[SPEAKER_06]: If you want your taxes cut, if you want your pension protected, if you want to get to net zero in a sensible way that doesn't saddle you with bills, if you want action on legal migration, on stopping the boats, I am the only person who is going to deliver that for you, and that is the choice at this election.

482
00:28:29,586 --> 00:28:32,813
[SPEAKER_07]: Before you go, Prime Minister, our time is coming to an end.

483
00:28:34,075 --> 00:28:40,287
[SPEAKER_07]: The polls would suggest this election hasn't gone brilliant for you, from D-Day to this betting scandal we've talked about.

484
00:28:40,307 --> 00:28:43,473
[SPEAKER_07]: Even the weather at one point seemed to be against you.

485
00:28:43,493 --> 00:28:45,396
[SPEAKER_07]: Do you regret calling the election early?

486
00:28:45,416 --> 00:28:47,861
[SPEAKER_07]: Do you not think another six months might have helped you turn it around?

487
00:28:47,881 --> 00:28:50,506
[SPEAKER_06]: No, because we touched on it earlier.

488
00:28:50,847 --> 00:28:54,193
[SPEAKER_06]: When I got this job, my number one

489
00:28:54,173 --> 00:28:57,021
[SPEAKER_06]: priority was to get the economy in a strong position.

490
00:28:57,603 --> 00:29:04,864
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's what we've been able to do over the last 18 months, get inflation back to target, get the economy growing, wages rising, energy bills falling.

491
00:29:05,165 --> 00:29:09,297
[SPEAKER_06]: So this is the moment for all of you to decide what future you want for our country.

492
00:29:09,277 --> 00:29:14,665
[SPEAKER_06]: and I want you to have that opportunity, and I'm very passionate and confident in what I'm saying.

493
00:29:15,266 --> 00:29:18,210
[SPEAKER_06]: I believe what I'm saying is right for our country and right for all of you.

494
00:29:18,551 --> 00:29:21,595
[SPEAKER_06]: I think you do want all your taxes cut, because you all work very hard.

495
00:29:21,956 --> 00:29:23,238
[SPEAKER_06]: You deserve to keep more of your money.

496
00:29:23,538 --> 00:29:27,023
[SPEAKER_06]: I want everyone to own their own home, like Rehan, so I want to cut taxes on him.

497
00:29:27,063 --> 00:29:34,474
[SPEAKER_06]: We haven't heard from, I think, any pensioners tonight, but if I'm not your Prime Minister for the first time in history, pensioners are going to face a retirement tax.

498
00:29:34,454 --> 00:29:36,917
[SPEAKER_06]: on their state pension in this country if I'm not your Prime Minister.

499
00:29:36,937 --> 00:29:38,419
[SPEAKER_06]: Because you froze the income tax at a threshold of levels.

500
00:29:38,439 --> 00:29:41,442
[SPEAKER_06]: And we're going to create the triple lock plus to make sure that doesn't happen.

501
00:29:41,502 --> 00:29:41,843
[SPEAKER_06]: It's your tax.

502
00:29:41,863 --> 00:29:42,143
[SPEAKER_06]: No, no, no.

503
00:29:42,163 --> 00:29:42,764
[SPEAKER_06]: That's your tax, though.

504
00:29:42,784 --> 00:29:43,044
[SPEAKER_06]: No, no, no.

505
00:29:43,064 --> 00:29:46,248
[SPEAKER_06]: You froze the income tax at a threshold that has dragged people into paying a high rate of tax.

506
00:29:46,288 --> 00:29:54,978
[SPEAKER_06]: Harry, in the next Parliament, if I'm not your Prime Minister, every pensioner is going to be paying a retirement tax for the first time in this country's history.

507
00:29:54,998 --> 00:29:56,800
[SPEAKER_06]: That won't happen if I'm your Prime Minister.

508
00:29:56,780 --> 00:30:07,171
[SPEAKER_06]: If I'm not your Prime Minister, you're all going to be paying thousands of pounds to upgrade your home, switch out your boiler, change your car, because Kirstarmer is going to reverse all the changes I made so we get to net zero in a sensible way.

509
00:30:07,491 --> 00:30:10,154
[SPEAKER_06]: Those illegal migrants will not be on planes to Rwanda.

510
00:30:10,374 --> 00:30:12,977
[SPEAKER_06]: They will be out on our streets, putting pressure on public services.

511
00:30:13,077 --> 00:30:19,564
[SPEAKER_06]: And by the way, I can tell you now, they are queuing up in Calais, waiting for a Starmer government so they can come here and stay here.

512
00:30:19,904 --> 00:30:22,367
[SPEAKER_08]: That is the choice.

513
00:30:22,387 --> 00:30:22,467
800.

514
00:30:22,447 --> 00:30:26,812
[SPEAKER_08]: 800 migrant crossings a day are happening on your watch, not Piers Darman's.

515
00:30:27,012 --> 00:30:28,914
[SPEAKER_06]: So that is a choice at this election, right?

516
00:30:28,954 --> 00:30:39,066
[SPEAKER_06]: I know people are frustrated about lots of things, but you've got to focus on that choice ahead of you and think about the next five years, think about what I'm saying, allow me to deliver all those things I just talked about for you.

517
00:30:39,226 --> 00:30:42,389
[SPEAKER_07]: Prime Minister, we're nearly at the end of our time, but how has it affected you?

518
00:30:42,409 --> 00:30:48,336
[SPEAKER_07]: You know, you're quite a tiggerish person, you're quite energetic, I think no-one would doubt you that,

519
00:30:48,316 --> 00:30:51,321
[SPEAKER_07]: But you've seen a little bit off-kilter since D-Day, really.

520
00:30:51,641 --> 00:30:52,923
[SPEAKER_07]: How has it affected you personally?

521
00:30:52,943 --> 00:30:54,185
[SPEAKER_07]: It feels like the sort of fight's gone.

522
00:30:54,205 --> 00:30:54,626
[SPEAKER_07]: What's happened?

523
00:30:54,806 --> 00:30:55,367
[SPEAKER_07]: That's not right.

524
00:30:55,467 --> 00:30:56,348
[SPEAKER_07]: It's not a fight.

525
00:30:56,368 --> 00:30:56,969
[SPEAKER_07]: A fight hasn't gone.

526
00:30:56,989 --> 00:30:58,672
[SPEAKER_06]: We've had a very tickerish conversation.

527
00:30:58,972 --> 00:31:02,357
[SPEAKER_06]: No, look, I am very passionate about this for a very simple reason, right?

528
00:31:02,377 --> 00:31:06,063
[SPEAKER_06]: Like, my grandparents came to this country with very little, right?

529
00:31:06,103 --> 00:31:07,405
[SPEAKER_06]: And here I am.

530
00:31:07,722 --> 00:31:12,769
[SPEAKER_06]: two generations later sitting here with the enormous privilege of being our country's prime minister.

531
00:31:13,310 --> 00:31:16,053
[SPEAKER_06]: I will never be able to repay that debt.

532
00:31:16,214 --> 00:31:18,877
[SPEAKER_06]: Everything that this country has done for me and my family is extraordinary.

533
00:31:19,178 --> 00:31:22,242
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's why I do this job, because I love this country.

534
00:31:22,322 --> 00:31:24,425
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm so grateful to everything that it's done for me.

535
00:31:24,926 --> 00:31:32,436
[SPEAKER_06]: And if you give me the honor of continuing to be your prime minister, I will work my socks off for you to deliver for all of you and make your lives better.

536
00:31:32,476 --> 00:31:35,400
[SPEAKER_06]: That's what I'm in this for, and that's why I have the energy to keep going.

537
00:31:35,380 --> 00:31:36,864
[SPEAKER_06]: Prime Minister, thank you very much.

538
00:31:36,884 --> 00:31:38,328
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you for coming to Neverland, Alex.

539
00:31:38,348 --> 00:31:39,571
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you for your questions.

540
00:31:39,591 --> 00:31:40,152
[SPEAKER_08]: Stay right there.

541
00:31:40,172 --> 00:31:41,456
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm staying here.

