1097
01:03:08,484 --> 01:03:12,710
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that's what the confusions came from when you first said it a few weeks ago.

1098
01:03:12,730 --> 01:03:13,872
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, just...

1099
01:03:14,223 --> 01:03:21,157
[SPEAKER_03]: I've been through life-threatening situations with my mum many, many times, holding her hand on nights we thought we were going to lose her.

1100
01:03:21,678 --> 01:03:24,484
[SPEAKER_03]: Too many times to not know exactly what that feels like.

1101
01:03:24,524 --> 01:03:31,759
[SPEAKER_03]: We had to go through it again, tragically, with my wife's mum in the leadership campaign, and we lost her in that particular

1102
01:03:31,739 --> 01:03:32,560
[SPEAKER_03]: case.

1103
01:03:33,161 --> 01:03:37,067
[SPEAKER_03]: I do know what I'm talking about when it comes to acute care in high dependency units.

1104
01:03:37,107 --> 01:03:43,738
[SPEAKER_03]: I know what it looks like, I know what it feels like, and I absolutely know it's the best place if you've got a life-threatening situation.

1105
01:03:43,758 --> 01:03:53,393
[SPEAKER_03]: Look, I'm not going to say to other people that's the choice that they should make, and the bigger choice, the bigger discussion that we're not really having here, which is important, is why are so many people having to now

1106
01:03:53,373 --> 01:03:56,757
[SPEAKER_03]: go private because they are having to wait so long on the NHS.

1107
01:03:56,777 --> 01:04:05,186
[SPEAKER_03]: The hard-working people are having to use their money, their savings, for operations which they ought to be able to get on the NHS much more quickly.

1108
01:04:05,446 --> 01:04:08,810
[SPEAKER_03]: It is the hidden tax in the NHS that we have got from this government.

1109
01:04:08,850 --> 01:04:10,491
[SPEAKER_03]: I want to end that.

1110
01:04:11,072 --> 01:04:18,520
[SPEAKER_03]: That is my choice, based on my experience, mainly on my mum, I accept, but I do know what the inside of a high-dependency unit looks like.

1111
01:04:18,500 --> 01:04:22,225
[SPEAKER_07]: We are running out of time, and your aides will shout at me if we go on too much longer.

1112
01:04:22,245 --> 01:04:23,707
[SPEAKER_07]: No, they won't, Harry.

1113
01:04:23,727 --> 01:04:25,630
[SPEAKER_07]: Dr Pasha, I think you had one more quick question.

1114
01:04:25,850 --> 01:04:26,311
[SPEAKER_07]: Very quick one.

1115
01:04:26,331 --> 01:04:27,653
[SPEAKER_07]: Keep it tight, keep it quick.

1116
01:04:28,354 --> 01:04:36,625
[SPEAKER_13]: Why are you trying to make it easier for people to change or switch their gender identity without sufficient proof?

1117
01:04:36,946 --> 01:04:43,495
[SPEAKER_13]: And what does this say to women's spaces and protecting them and their spaces?

1118
01:04:46,900 --> 01:04:48,422
[SPEAKER_03]: Women's spaces must be protected.

1119
01:04:49,023 --> 01:04:50,325
[SPEAKER_03]: It's very, very important.

1120
01:04:50,585 --> 01:04:58,837
[SPEAKER_03]: And again, when I was chief prosecutor, I was working with very many people who had been victims of sexual violence and domestic violence.

1121
01:04:58,877 --> 01:05:00,379
[SPEAKER_03]: It was a big part of the work I was doing.

1122
01:05:00,679 --> 01:05:06,327
[SPEAKER_03]: And I saw for myself how important those women's spaces are, and they must be protected.

1123
01:05:06,307 --> 01:05:12,155
[SPEAKER_03]: whether it's in that area, whether it's single-sex wards or sport, that must be protected.

1124
01:05:12,856 --> 01:05:20,446
[SPEAKER_03]: We mustn't go down the route of self-identification, but we do need to recognise the procedure or the process at the moment is not dignified.

1125
01:05:20,606 --> 01:05:25,172
[SPEAKER_03]: There are some people who don't identify with the gender that they're born into.

1126
01:05:25,212 --> 01:05:28,637
[SPEAKER_03]: They are very distressed by that.

1127
01:05:29,237 --> 01:05:33,563
[SPEAKER_03]: And my rule in life is to treat everybody with respect,

1128
01:05:33,543 --> 01:05:37,167
[SPEAKER_03]: and dignity, and that's what I will do, but we must protect safe spaces.

1129
01:05:37,187 --> 01:05:39,450
[SPEAKER_07]: Zakir, we're running... We're approaching the end of our time.

1130
01:05:39,470 --> 01:05:45,416
[SPEAKER_07]: Why do people like JK Rowling think that you've abandoned... You know, have accused you of abandoning women, Labour of abandoning women.

1131
01:05:45,436 --> 01:05:47,118
[SPEAKER_07]: Why do... What's gone wrong there?

1132
01:05:47,138 --> 01:05:52,364
[SPEAKER_03]: Look, I respect what she says, and I think I welcome the debate.

1133
01:05:53,465 --> 01:05:59,432
[SPEAKER_07]: She said that Labour are behaving like a husband who's cheating on his wife but expects her to be OK with it because he always takes the bins out.

1134
01:06:00,577 --> 01:06:02,559
[SPEAKER_07]: What do you think she meant by that?

1135
01:06:02,579 --> 01:06:05,562
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, look, I actually do really respect what she said.

1136
01:06:05,702 --> 01:06:07,044
[SPEAKER_03]: Are you going to have a meeting with her?

1137
01:06:07,064 --> 01:06:07,985
[SPEAKER_03]: Are you going to try and bring her back?

1138
01:06:08,005 --> 01:06:08,926
[SPEAKER_03]: She used to be a Labour donor.

1139
01:06:09,206 --> 01:06:10,127
[SPEAKER_03]: Of course I'd meet with her.

1140
01:06:10,307 --> 01:06:10,908
[SPEAKER_03]: Of course I would.

1141
01:06:10,968 --> 01:06:13,911
[SPEAKER_03]: And, you know, again, my approach in life...

1142
01:06:13,931 --> 01:06:15,132
[SPEAKER_03]: I came into politics really late.

1143
01:06:15,553 --> 01:06:17,155
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm not as tribal as everybody else.

1144
01:06:17,495 --> 01:06:19,817
[SPEAKER_03]: I've run out of, you know, operations.

1145
01:06:19,857 --> 01:06:21,119
[SPEAKER_03]: I ran a public service.

1146
01:06:21,139 --> 01:06:25,183
[SPEAKER_03]: My view is, if there's an issue or a challenge, roll up your sleeves, get people round the table,

1147
01:06:25,163 --> 01:06:27,646
[SPEAKER_03]: and talk through the issues and find a way forward.

1148
01:06:27,666 --> 01:06:30,188
[SPEAKER_03]: So I'll always talk to anyone about this.

1149
01:06:30,208 --> 01:06:34,974
[SPEAKER_03]: The only rule, I suppose, I'd set is we've got to treat each other with respect.

1150
01:06:35,494 --> 01:06:42,602
[SPEAKER_03]: J.K. Rowling, I respect her and I don't suggest for a minute that she hasn't... She's made some really important points.

1151
01:06:43,142 --> 01:06:50,731
[SPEAKER_03]: I'd welcome that discussion because I do think that we've made huge progress on women's rights under Labour governments and equality, massive progress.

1152
01:06:51,031 --> 01:06:52,993
[SPEAKER_03]: There's more work to be done if we are...

1153
01:06:52,973 --> 01:07:00,150
[SPEAKER_03]: privileged to come in to serve this country, and I want to make sure that we can bring people together and, you know, take our country forward as well.

1154
01:07:00,170 --> 01:07:00,831
[SPEAKER_03]: Do comments like that get to you?

1155
01:07:00,851 --> 01:07:01,433
[SPEAKER_07]: You really ready?

1156
01:07:01,473 --> 01:07:08,429
[SPEAKER_07]: You're about to, if the polls have been to believe, walk down Downing Street in ten days' time with a super majority, but are you ready for it?

1157
01:07:09,111 --> 01:07:10,594
[SPEAKER_07]: Is it sunk in yet?

1158
01:07:10,574 --> 01:07:11,576
[SPEAKER_03]: We are not...

1159
01:07:11,596 --> 01:07:15,422
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, I respect voters too much to presume anything.

1160
01:07:16,464 --> 01:07:18,468
[SPEAKER_03]: We have to earn every vote.

1161
01:07:18,508 --> 01:07:21,433
[SPEAKER_03]: But, I mean, if the polls are to be believed, it's going to be a supermajority.

1162
01:07:21,453 --> 01:07:23,196
[SPEAKER_03]: Polls don't predict the future.

1163
01:07:23,256 --> 01:07:25,280
[SPEAKER_03]: Do you know what you'd do with a supermajority?

1164
01:07:25,300 --> 01:07:27,283
[SPEAKER_03]: What I would say for this...

1165
01:07:27,263 --> 01:07:28,084
[SPEAKER_03]: is this.

1166
01:07:28,124 --> 01:07:29,266
[SPEAKER_03]: This is a change election.

1167
01:07:29,326 --> 01:07:30,868
[SPEAKER_03]: We've had 14 years of this now.

1168
01:07:31,328 --> 01:07:32,670
[SPEAKER_03]: We know things aren't working.

1169
01:07:32,690 --> 01:07:34,412
[SPEAKER_03]: I think everybody knows it in their bones.

1170
01:07:34,472 --> 01:07:35,914
[SPEAKER_03]: They tell me this across the country.

1171
01:07:36,215 --> 01:07:37,436
[SPEAKER_03]: Things are really broken.

1172
01:07:37,537 --> 01:07:40,661
[SPEAKER_03]: People are really frustrated, quite worried about the future.

1173
01:07:41,101 --> 01:07:42,944
[SPEAKER_03]: We need... We can't go on like this.

1174
01:07:43,164 --> 01:07:49,592
[SPEAKER_03]: Have you seen any evidence in this election that the Tory party has changed, is going to be different if it comes into power?

1175
01:07:49,612 --> 01:07:50,534
[SPEAKER_03]: They're busy...

1176
01:07:50,554 --> 01:07:54,459
[SPEAKER_03]: The first instinct about the date of the election is not go out... We've done the betting.

1177
01:07:54,479 --> 01:07:55,380
[SPEAKER_03]: We've done the betting.

1178
01:07:55,360 --> 01:07:56,482
[SPEAKER_03]: But they're not changed.

1179
01:07:56,502 --> 01:08:00,469
[SPEAKER_03]: So we have the chance now for change to turn the page, rebuild with Labour.

1180
01:08:00,489 --> 01:08:04,236
[SPEAKER_03]: But change is only going to happen if people go out and vote for it.

1181
01:08:04,256 --> 01:08:05,859
[SPEAKER_03]: So I'm taking nothing for granted.

1182
01:08:06,921 --> 01:08:13,453
[SPEAKER_03]: And we will fight for every vote until the close of the day on election day a week on Thursday.

1183
01:08:13,433 --> 01:08:15,035
[SPEAKER_07]: Entourage is waiting.

1184
01:08:15,055 --> 01:08:15,656
[SPEAKER_07]: You've got to go.

1185
01:08:15,676 --> 01:08:16,437
[SPEAKER_07]: We've had a lot of time.

1186
01:08:16,457 --> 01:08:18,220
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm just going to ask you one more question, if you don't mind.

1187
01:08:18,660 --> 01:08:24,268
[SPEAKER_07]: Last time you came on Never Mind the Ballots, I said that I would read the book about you, cos you'd read the book I wrote about you.

1188
01:08:24,288 --> 01:08:24,869
[SPEAKER_07]: I read your book.

1189
01:08:24,889 --> 01:08:25,389
[SPEAKER_07]: Exactly.

1190
01:08:25,570 --> 01:08:28,714
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, I did read your book, and I found a really interesting line in it.

1191
01:08:29,295 --> 01:08:36,284
[SPEAKER_07]: One of your former advisors said that you're not the sort of person that would set out a radical vision and then have to row back.

1192
01:08:36,645 --> 01:08:41,972
[SPEAKER_07]: You're the sort of person that would exhaust conventional options and then eventually become...

1193
01:08:41,952 --> 01:08:42,673
[SPEAKER_07]: more radical.

1194
01:08:43,174 --> 01:08:46,080
[SPEAKER_07]: Is that what Britain's about to get as Keir Starmer's Prime Minister?

1195
01:08:46,180 --> 01:08:51,311
[SPEAKER_07]: You're saying, not all everything now, but actually, secretly, you're plotting something quite big.

1196
01:08:51,391 --> 01:08:52,032
[SPEAKER_07]: Oh, no, we are.

1197
01:08:52,052 --> 01:08:57,603
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, for the NHS, for example, I think job number one is to put it back on its feet, get it working again, get those waiting lists down.

1198
01:08:57,864 --> 01:09:00,990
[SPEAKER_03]: But we are ambitious about actually changing the NHS.

1199
01:09:00,970 --> 01:09:03,815
[SPEAKER_03]: so that it's fit for the next 75, 76 years, for example.

1200
01:09:03,835 --> 01:09:04,656
[SPEAKER_03]: That's a big job.

1201
01:09:04,997 --> 01:09:07,161
[SPEAKER_03]: The Labour Party, Labour government set up the NHS.

1202
01:09:07,201 --> 01:09:08,824
[SPEAKER_03]: That's one of the proudest things we've ever done.

1203
01:09:09,164 --> 01:09:10,867
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't want forever to be looking back.

1204
01:09:10,967 --> 01:09:18,721
[SPEAKER_03]: I want to make sure that for future generations, they can say that the 2024 government got to grips with making sure the NHS was fit for the future.

1205
01:09:18,741 --> 01:09:23,569
[SPEAKER_07]: And you're confident you don't have to raise any further taxes than you set out in your manifesto?

1206
01:09:23,549 --> 01:09:24,210
[SPEAKER_03]: to pay for it?

1207
01:09:24,350 --> 01:09:39,392
[SPEAKER_03]: No, we've set out... Our manifesto has got a schedule at the back of it, costing everything we've said we're going to do, and saying where the money is coming from, because we know from Liz Truss, if you don't do that, then you damage the economy and working people are paying the price.

1208
01:09:39,412 --> 01:09:43,077
[SPEAKER_03]: And I think it was a question earlier from somebody about mortgages.

1209
01:09:43,057 --> 01:09:52,051
[SPEAKER_03]: And I've met so many people who have come off their fixed-rate mortgage in the last couple of years and now having to pay hundreds of pounds more because of what the Tories did to the economy.

1210
01:09:52,071 --> 01:09:56,778
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm never going to let a Labour government do that, which is why everything is fully costed and fully funded.

1211
01:09:56,798 --> 01:09:58,861
[SPEAKER_07]: Sir Keir Starmer, I think we've heard lots.

1212
01:09:59,062 --> 01:09:59,703
[SPEAKER_07]: You've heard lots.

1213
01:09:59,883 --> 01:10:01,205
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you for coming to Nevermind the Ballot.

1214
01:10:02,667 --> 01:10:05,812
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you for having me.

1215
01:10:05,832 --> 01:10:09,638
[SPEAKER_07]: Just before you go... And I'm sorry, if I didn't have going last, you'd have to see this bit.

1216
01:10:10,428 --> 01:10:14,873
[SPEAKER_07]: Hands up, who thought Sakir Starmer performed better than Rishi Sunak?

1217
01:10:16,034 --> 01:10:17,256
[SPEAKER_07]: Oh, it's quite split.

1218
01:10:17,276 --> 01:10:19,599
[SPEAKER_07]: Who thought Rishi Sunak was the winner?

1219
01:10:19,619 --> 01:10:19,799
[SPEAKER_07]: Oh.

1220
01:10:21,060 --> 01:10:24,905
[SPEAKER_07]: Who thinks we've learnt more about what Sakir Starmer might do in ten days?

1221
01:10:26,567 --> 01:10:27,347
[SPEAKER_07]: Oh, not as many hands.

1222
01:10:28,309 --> 01:10:28,929
[SPEAKER_07]: And who trusts him?

1223
01:10:30,551 --> 01:10:31,392
[SPEAKER_07]: There you go, not bad.

1224
01:10:31,412 --> 01:10:31,752
[SPEAKER_07]: Not bad.

1225
01:10:32,033 --> 01:10:32,373
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1226
01:10:32,393 --> 01:10:33,274
[SPEAKER_07]: Sakir Starmer, thank you very much.

1227
01:10:33,294 --> 01:10:33,955
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you for having me.

1228
01:10:35,032 --> 01:10:36,854
[SPEAKER_07]: Right, let's cross back to Kate.

1229
01:10:36,874 --> 01:10:42,101
[SPEAKER_07]: She has the post-match analysis and the very, very sophisticated polling numbers of putting up hands.

1230
01:10:42,762 --> 01:10:43,222
[SPEAKER_10]: Thanks, Kate.

1231
01:10:43,883 --> 01:10:44,344
[SPEAKER_10]: Thanks, Harry.

1232
01:10:44,384 --> 01:10:51,933
[SPEAKER_10]: And still joining me in the studio is, of course, Gillian Keegan, Tory Education Secretary, and Jonathan Ashworth, the Shadow Paymaster General.

1233
01:10:52,253 --> 01:10:54,196
[SPEAKER_10]: Well, plenty to get stuck into there.

1234
01:10:54,817 --> 01:10:56,258
[SPEAKER_10]: Jonathan, I'll come to you first.

1235
01:10:56,699 --> 01:11:01,545
[SPEAKER_10]: Keir looked awkward when he was asked about Jeremy Corbyn, his previous support for Jeremy Corbyn.

1236
01:11:01,897 --> 01:11:05,265
[SPEAKER_10]: Do you agree with Kerr that Corbyn would have made a better PM than Boris Johnson?

1237
01:11:05,626 --> 01:11:11,560
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, if you recall the last election, it was what my views were.

1238
01:11:11,921 --> 01:11:14,647
[SPEAKER_04]: I think you wrote about what my views were at the time.

1239
01:11:14,667 --> 01:11:15,028
[SPEAKER_04]: Look.

1240
01:11:15,245 --> 01:11:22,117
[SPEAKER_04]: You're talking about a leaked conversation you had when you criticised Corbyn.

1241
01:11:22,137 --> 01:11:24,200
[SPEAKER_04]: No, I didn't vote for Jeremy Corbyn to be leader of the Labour Party.

1242
01:11:24,220 --> 01:11:25,262
[SPEAKER_04]: And neither did Keir Starmer.

1243
01:11:25,443 --> 01:11:27,887
[SPEAKER_04]: He voted against Jeremy Corbyn twice.

1244
01:11:28,508 --> 01:11:32,755
[SPEAKER_04]: He actually wrote to Jeremy Corbyn making it clear what he thought of his leadership.

1245
01:11:33,236 --> 01:11:38,485
[SPEAKER_04]: But of course, we knew we were heading for the almighty hammering in those elections.

1246
01:11:38,465 --> 01:11:44,974
[SPEAKER_04]: And we had to do all we could to get as many good Labour colleagues elected, because we would have to rebuild this party from the ashes.

1247
01:11:44,994 --> 01:11:48,359
[SPEAKER_04]: And what Keir has done since has completely transformed this party.

1248
01:11:48,780 --> 01:11:50,142
[SPEAKER_04]: Jeremy Corbyn isn't a Labour candidate.

1249
01:11:50,562 --> 01:11:52,205
[SPEAKER_04]: Liz Truss is still a Tory candidate.

1250
01:11:52,225 --> 01:11:52,805
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's the difference.

1251
01:11:52,825 --> 01:11:54,508
[SPEAKER_09]: It's just a complete rewriting of history.

1252
01:11:54,808 --> 01:12:00,036
[SPEAKER_09]: And actually, David Lammy, the guy who wants to be Foreign Secretary, nominated Jeremy Corbyn.

1253
01:12:00,056 --> 01:12:07,206
[SPEAKER_09]: Jeremy Corbyn, who literally, if we'd have looked at, you know, Keir praised Boris about Ukraine.

1254
01:12:07,186 --> 01:12:09,730
[SPEAKER_09]: They'd have got their way, and Jeremy Corbyn was there.

1255
01:12:09,870 --> 01:12:12,914
[SPEAKER_09]: What would he have done when Ukraine was invaded?

1256
01:12:13,315 --> 01:12:16,099
[SPEAKER_09]: We don't even know he'd be on the side of the Ukrainians.

1257
01:12:16,239 --> 01:12:17,721
[SPEAKER_09]: It is such a serious thing.

1258
01:12:17,741 --> 01:12:22,828
[SPEAKER_09]: Jonathan, I wonder if you... And also, second referendum, you cannot... You can't just constantly change...

1259
01:12:22,848 --> 01:12:25,071
[SPEAKER_09]: These are positions, like, four, five years ago.

1260
01:12:25,492 --> 01:12:27,334
[SPEAKER_09]: Constantly changing your positions.

1261
01:12:27,895 --> 01:12:33,283
[SPEAKER_09]: You know, wait until everything else has been sorted out and then saying, ah, actually, that's what I'm...

1262
01:12:33,303 --> 01:12:34,364
[SPEAKER_09]: I want to ask Jonathan something.

1263
01:12:34,404 --> 01:12:37,108
[SPEAKER_10]: Jonathan, do you regret serving on Jeremy's front bench now?

1264
01:12:37,088 --> 01:12:47,763
[SPEAKER_04]: No, I was doing all I could to get as many good Labour colleagues re-elected, because I knew we were going to get absolutely hammered in general elections.

1265
01:12:47,843 --> 01:12:51,388
[SPEAKER_04]: And look, I've been a member of this Labour Party since I was 15, right?

1266
01:12:51,548 --> 01:12:55,854
[SPEAKER_04]: The Labour Party, I believe, has been one of the greatest forces for social justice our country's seen.

1267
01:12:55,874 --> 01:12:57,155
[SPEAKER_04]: We created the National Health Service.

1268
01:12:57,196 --> 01:12:58,297
[SPEAKER_04]: We introduced the minimum...

1269
01:12:58,317 --> 01:12:59,699
[SPEAKER_04]: Create unemployment.

1270
01:12:59,779 --> 01:13:00,480
[SPEAKER_04]: Let me finish.

1271
01:13:00,460 --> 01:13:02,203
[SPEAKER_04]: We introduced the national minimum wage.

1272
01:13:02,544 --> 01:13:05,248
[SPEAKER_04]: We introduced things like Sure Start centres and tax credits.

1273
01:13:05,268 --> 01:13:12,200
[SPEAKER_04]: In the 1960s, we introduced a whole load of reforms around gay rights and race discrimination.

1274
01:13:12,561 --> 01:13:18,571
[SPEAKER_04]: I was always going to fight for the Labour Party because I knew that a group of us would have to rebuild the Labour Party.

1275
01:13:18,591 --> 01:13:19,873
[SPEAKER_04]: And we've changed the Labour Party.

1276
01:13:20,214 --> 01:13:21,396
[SPEAKER_04]: Jeremy Corbyn is not a candidate.

1277
01:13:21,696 --> 01:13:23,119
[SPEAKER_04]: Liz Truss is a Tory candidate.

1278
01:13:23,740 --> 01:13:26,164
[SPEAKER_04]: And if you want change in this country, you've got to vote Labour.

1279
01:13:26,245 --> 01:13:30,537
[SPEAKER_10]: So one thing that came up in that interview, Gillian, was borders.

1280
01:13:30,938 --> 01:13:31,259
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah.

1281
